"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90445","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-09-08","<p>Details of Ministers’ visits are published quarterly and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dcms-meetings-and-hospitality-data-october-to-december-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dcms-meetings-and-hospitality-data-october-to-december-2013</a></p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-09-08T13:09:47.153759Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90445/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90445/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-09-03","Domestic Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 10 July 2014, Official Report, column 13W, on domestic visits, what domestic visits he and his predecessor has made since January 2013; and what the purpose of each such visit was.","false","Biography information for Sheila Gilmore","Edinburgh East","Sheila Gilmore","208005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90446","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-09-09","<p><strong>I have not had discussions with FIFA or UEFA on this matter, however, I am assured by the Premier League that UK based Premier League players taking part in this fixture took advice from their individual club doctors. We understand that none of the players and staff of the Sierra Leone team had entered Sierra Leone in the 21 days up to the fixture as requested by the Ivory Coast and this was viewed to be an effective a quarantine measure.</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>The Department of Health advised that the risk of Ebola infection at a football match is considered low. Exit screening measures, including body temperature measurement when leaving affected countries, are in place.</strong></p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-09-09T09:17:10.4333717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90446/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90446/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-09-03","Ebola: West Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will have discussions with UEFA and FIFA on the Ebola infection risk arising from the decision to stage the Ivory Coast versus Sierra Leone football match on 6 September 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","208060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90447","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-09-08","<p>DCMS does not have any direct employees who are paid less than the rate defined by the Living Wage Foundation as a living wage.</p><p> </p><p>DCMS is not responsible for setting pay levels for contracted workers. This is a matter for the organisations who employ them. However, we actively encourage employers to ensure that the living wage is paid and we would monitor these when contracts are being negotiated.</p><p> </p><p>We do not hold central records for our arms lengths bodies.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-09-08T13:15:26.8045983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90447/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90447/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-09-03","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) direct employees, (b) outsourced workers and (c) agency workers in executive agencies which report to his Department are paid less than the Living Wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","208011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90448","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-12","<p> </p><p>The costs to manage and maintain Service Family Accommodation (SFA) are broadly the same whether the accommodation is occupied or vacant.</p><p> </p><p>No calculation of lost income for vacant properties is made.</p><p> </p><p>The percentage of vacant SFA properties is shown below:</p><p> </p><p>As at 31 March 2010 2011 2012 2013 2014</p><p> </p><p>Void Percentage 15% 12% 13% 16% 19%</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This gradual increase in vacant properties is due to preparation for the return of personnel from Germany.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-09-12T13:04:57.755725Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90448/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90448/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90448/answer/previousversion/19383","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the (a) management, (b) maintenance and (c) lost income costs of empty service accommodation were in each of the last five years; and what (i) size and (ii) type of properties have been vacant in that period.","false","Biography information for Alison Seabeck","Plymouth, Moor View","Alison Seabeck","208036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90449","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-09","<p>We continue to make excellent progress on the competition for the Managed Service Providers (MSPs) and expect to place the first contracts in the next few weeks. <br><br>The MSPs will have an important role in supporting the transformation of Defence Equipment and Support (DE&amp;S) into a world class programme management organisation, capable of delivering the best possible equipment and support to our Armed Forces. Strengthening the relationship between the Service Commands and DE&amp;S is a key aspect of the transformation programme.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-09-09T16:33:55.4599272Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90449/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90449/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether he plans to let the contracts for the managed service providers (MSP) before the end of September 2014; and if he will place relationship with the services and Defence Equipment and Support.","false","Biography information for Alison Seabeck","Plymouth, Moor View","Alison Seabeck","208062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90450","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-08","<p>The UK does not hold such information as it pertains to the Alliance as a whole.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier","208054","2014-09-08T16:00:47.1378818Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90450/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90450/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many nuclear warheads have been (a) lost and (b) lost and not recovered by NATO in the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","208050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90451","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 5 September 2014, (Official Report, column 363w) to the hon. Member for Plymouth, Sutton &amp; Devonport (Mr Colvile).<br><br>As a new class of Royal Navy warship, the naming of the Type 26 Frigates will follow a theme, and this is under consideration. The Ships' Names and Badges Committee has noted the proposal to use names of UK cities.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-09-09T16:33:15.9226561Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90451/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90451/answer","20140905 - Hansard extract Warships[1].doc","20140905 - Hansard extract Warships[1].doc","20140905 - Hansard extract Warships","20140905 - Hansard extract Warships","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90451/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Warships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what process the Royal Navy uses when deciding the names of new vessels; and whether names of UK cities can be used for the Type 26.","false","Biography information for Alison Seabeck","Plymouth, Moor View","Alison Seabeck","208052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90452","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-08","<p>The Regular Army Reserve of Officers allows the Army to recall individuals who have previously served in the Army to assist in the nation’s defence and provide a national strategic Reserve capability. Under Army 2020 the Regular Army Reserve of Officers will, as now, provide a valuable pool of skills and expertise that can be called upon as and when a situation of national crisis demands it. There are no plans to change the role of the Regular Army Reserve of Officers as part of the plans to increase the size of the Army Reserve to 30,000 as the two are constituted for different roles and capabilities.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier","208084","2014-09-08T15:22:50.7228078Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90452/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90452/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Army Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Regular Army Reserve of Officers will play any role in his plans for an expanded Territorial Army; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugh Robertson","Faversham and Mid Kent","Sir Hugh Robertson","208083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90453","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-08","<p>The Regular Army Reserve of Officers allows the Army to recall individuals who have previously served in the Army to assist in the nation’s defence and provide a national strategic Reserve capability. Under Army 2020 the Regular Army Reserve of Officers will, as now, provide a valuable pool of skills and expertise that can be called upon as and when a situation of national crisis demands it. There are no plans to change the role of the Regular Army Reserve of Officers as part of the plans to increase the size of the Army Reserve to 30,000 as the two are constituted for different roles and capabilities.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier","208083","2014-09-08T15:22:50.6598997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90453/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90453/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Army Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many members the Regular Army Reserve of Officers has.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugh Robertson","Faversham and Mid Kent","Sir Hugh Robertson","208084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90454","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-10","<p>The Strategic Business Partner Contract has obligations to manage all the services managed by the Defence Infrastructure Organisation including the service delivery contracts. These contracts include customer service and response times. <br><br>The Strategic Business Partner Contract also contains key performance indicators for customer satisfaction.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-09-10T13:09:16.4771978Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90454/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90454/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Defence Infrastructure Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the contract for the strategic business partnership between the Defence Infrastructure Organisation and Capita contains conditions on customer facing service and expected response times to enquiries.","false","Biography information for Alison Seabeck","Plymouth, Moor View","Alison Seabeck","208037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90455","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-10","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 14 October 2013, (Official Report, column 483W).</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-09-10T13:08:35.0953586Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90455/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90455/answer","Historical Enquiries Team.doc 14 October 2013.doc","Historical Enquiries Team.doc 14 October 2013.doc","Hansard Extract 14 October 2013","Hansard Extract 14 October 2013","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90455/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90455/answer/previousversion/18958","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Public Records: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what current assessment he has made of the relevance of unreleased historical documents relating to Northern Ireland held at Swadlincote to the work of the Historical Enquiries Team in investigating cases from the past; and whether he plans to release these records to the National Archive under the Public Records Act 1958.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","207980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90456","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-10","<p>.The total budget of the Armoured Vehicles Programme in each financial year (FY) since 2010 has been:<br><br>FY Expenditure (£ million)<br>2010-11 399<br>2011-12 391<br>2012-13 373<br>2013-14 357<br>2014-15 463<br><br>The estimate of the budget of this programme in each FY of the latest 10 year Equipment Plan up to 2025 is:<br><br>FY Expenditure (£ million)<br>2015-16 496<br>2016-17 592<br>2017-18 885<br>2018-19 1,047<br>2019-20 1,301<br>2020-21 1,534<br>2021-22 1,667<br>2022-23 1,717<br>2023-24 1,667<br>2024-25 1,294<br><br>Figures do not include non-Equipment Programme costs such as fuel, training and consumable inventory.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-09-10T16:42:34.669059Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90456/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90456/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the total budget of the Armoured Vehicles Programme has been in each year since 2010; and what estimate he has made of the budget of this programme in each year upto 2030.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","208110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90457","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-10","<p>The Ministry of Defence is no longer pursuing a “Future Rapid Effects System” programme. The capability that the Future Rapid Effects System was intended to deliver is now being delivered through other projects, principally the SCOUT Specialist Vehicle (SV) and the Utility Vehicle (UV). SCOUT is the transformational project that will refresh our entire armoured capability and allow us to remain a global first-tier military force. <br><br>A £3.5 billion contract to procure 589 SCOUT (SVs) was announced by my right hon .Friend the Secretary of State for Defence (Michael Fallon) on 3 September 2014 (Official Report, column 20WS). The Utility Vehicle programme, including work to define the requirements of the vehicle, is in its early stages.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-09-10T13:11:44.2734263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90457/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90457/answer","Defence.Doc WMS Defence Procurement 3 September.doc","Defence.Doc WMS Defence Procurement 3 September.doc","WMS Defence Procurement 3 September","WMS Defence Procurement 3 September","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90457/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to procure a class of Future Rapid Effects System Utility vehicles as part of the Armoured Vehicles Programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","208112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90458","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-10","<p>The previous Defence Secretary, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), outlined changes to streamline the Army Reserve structure under the Future Reserves 2020 plan on 3 July 2013 (Official Report: Column 49WS). <br><br>The result of this plan was that a number of Army Reserve Centres were identified as surplus to Army requirements and would therefore be closed. Since then plans to pair Reserve units with Regular units have been developed and the Army has undertaken further work to ensure the optimum geographical footprint is in place. This work has taken into account recruiting performance, long term value for money and the delivery of operational capability. As a result of this work some units previously scheduled for closure will now remain open. Others may also remain open, subject to significantly improved recruiting performance before 2016. Members affected by these changes will be notified at the time and I intend to keep Parliament updated on these changes on an annual basis.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2014-09-10T13:17:56.3873493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90458/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90458/answer","Defence.doc WMS 3 July 2013.doc","Defence.doc WMS 3 July 2013.doc","WMS Extract Army Reserve 3 July 2013","WMS Extract Army Reserve 3 July 2013","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90458/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Army Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when a decision will be taken on the long-term future of Army Reserve bases which had originally been scheduled to be closed in 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","208104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90459","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-08","<p>The UK does not hold such information as it pertains to the Alliance as a whole.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier","208050","2014-09-08T16:00:47.231588Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90459/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90459/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will provide details of each accident involving a nuclear weapon deployed outside of the US in support of NATO in the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","208054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90460","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-09","<p>I am withholding the information as its disclosure would prejudice commercial interests.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-09-09T16:32:39.0792932Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90460/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90460/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-03","Challenger Tanks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department will spend in each year under the Challenger II Life Extension programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","208108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90461","Department for Education","false","2014-09-09","<p>Maintained secondary schools must teach a modern foreign language to all pupils at key stage 3 (ages 11-14). The choice of which language or languages to teach is for schools to make, though the great majority of secondary schools teach one or more of French, German or Spanish, with small numbers teaching an additional language or languages.</p><p> </p><p>Awarding bodies determine which languages they will offer as GCSE qualifications. Schools decide whether to enter pupils for any particular language GCSE. The English Baccalaureate is already encouraging more young people to take a language at GCSE level. Take-up of a modern foreign language by key stage 4 pupils in England increased by over 20% between 2012 and 2013.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb",,"2014-09-09T16:06:36.3305997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90461/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90461/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-09-03","Languages: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to broaden the number of foreign language subjects available to state school students in secondary education.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","208097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90462","Department for Education","false","2014-09-08","<p>It is not possible to identify pupils entered for Mandarin Chinese from the Department for Education’s data. However, the Department does hold information on the number of entries into GCSE Chinese which includes Mandarin Chinese and other Chinese subjects. In the academic year 2010/11, there were 2,480 entries for GCSE Mandarin, 2,307 in the academic year 2011/12 and 2,346 in the academic year 2012/13. This information is published in the GCSE statistical first release.[1]</p><p><br> [1]<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/gcse-and-equivalent-results-in-england-2012-to-2013-revised" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/gcse-and-equivalent-results-in-england-2012-to-2013-revised</a> (Subject time series table)</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-09-08T13:35:24.6924356Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90462/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90462/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-09-03","Mandarin: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many students in state schools secondary education obtained a GCSE in Mandarin Chinese in each year since Janaury 2011.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","208111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90463","Department for Education","false","2014-09-09","<p>Schools are legally required to secure independent careers guidance for 12- to 18-year-olds that includes information on the full range of education and training options, including apprenticeships.</p><p>In 2013, Ofsted’s study of the early implementation of this duty found that apprenticeships were rarely promoted effectively, especially in schools with sixth forms.</p><p>The Government has published new statutory guidance and departmental advice on careers guidance and inspiration, informed by the Ofsted study, which is effective from September 2014. This provides a clear framework and practical support for schools to help them inspire their pupils about the options open to them. The guidance is clear that schools should give employers and other providers delivering apprenticeships the opportunity to inform pupils directly about what they offer. It emphasises that apprenticeships and university offer two equally effective routes to a successful career.</p><p>Ofsted is now giving careers guidance a higher priority in school inspections and we will work with them to monitor carefully the impact of the statutory guidance and the wider improvements that the Government has put in place.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-09-09T13:34:43.6439424Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90463/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90463/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-09-03","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment she has made of the role of schools in encouraging pupils to consider apprenticeships post-16.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","207983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90464","Department for Education","false","2014-09-08","<p>The Government has no plans to review the statutory guidance for children’s centres on the sharing of live birth data.</p><p>The Department for Education’s Sure Start children’s centres statutory guidance says that health services and local authorities should share information (such as live birth data and data on families with children under five who have recently moved into the area) with children’s centres on a regular basis.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2014-09-08T16:25:44.5566935Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90464/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90464/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-09-03","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will review the adequacy of current statutory guidance on the sharing of live birth data with children's centres.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","208025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90465","Department for Education","false","2014-09-08","<p>A robust assessment of the needs of a child and their family and how these needs will be met through on-going support from the local authority is crucial if children are to return home safely and successfully from care. Improving practice when children return home from care is a priority for the Government.</p><p>In September 2013, the Government published the ‘Improving Permanence for looked-after children’ data pack, which is published online:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/improving-permanence-for-looked-after-children-data-pack" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/improving-permanence-for-looked-after-children-data-pack</a></p><p>The data pack encourages local authorities to consider their own systems and processes for returning children home and to improving their rate of success.</p><p>In 2013 the Department consulted on a range of proposals to improve permanence for looked-after children. Department for Education officials have convened a meeting of the relevant Expert Group on 9 September to discuss these issues and the Government’s formal response will be published later this year.</p><p>The Government has commissioned the National Children’s Bureau (NCB) and the Centre for Child and Family Research (CCFR) at Loughborough University to deliver an action research project. The project is working with frontline practitioners and families to support improved practice in returning children home.</p><p>This project is complemented by research we have commissioned from the NSPCC and the University of Bristol. Their approach is ‘top down’, working with senior practitioners to implement a specific model of support for children returning home, developed and tested by NSPCC. This research will build on earlier work by NSPCC and includes a focus on implementation science, identifying savings and efficiencies, and developing a practice model that can be used by local authorities without the need for specialist support from the NSPCC.</p><p>Both of these research projects will report in 2015.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-09-08T16:57:28.624155Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90465/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90465/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-09-03","Children: Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking in response to research in the NSPCC's report, Returning home from care.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","208034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90466","Department for Education","false","2014-09-08","<p>The Department for Education has not commissioned any research to date specifically on the role of special educational needs coordinators (SENCOs) in decisions on how to spend the pupil premium, just as the Department does not advise schools in any general sense on how they should spend the pupil premium. This is because schools are best placed to understand and respond to the needs of their disadvantaged pupils, and to develop their own processes for deciding pupil premium spending priorities. Schools will of course wish to involve SENCOs in reviewing the evidence on effective practice in raising the attainment of disadvantaged pupils with special educational needs, and use their findings to inform spending decisions.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-09-08T16:59:41.1697177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90466/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90466/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-09-03","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 1 July 2014, Official Report, column 551W, on disadvantaged pupils, what research her Department has commissioned into the role of special educational needs co-ordinators in decisions on how to spend the Pupil Premium; and for what reason no guidance was issued to schools on this matter.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","208026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90467","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-09-12","<p>The Government is actively encouraging all householders, whether on or off the gas grid, to invest in energy efficiency and reduce their energy bills.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-12T13:11:32.9085579Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90467/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/90467/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-09-03","Boilers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what further steps he plans to take to encourage the upgrade of boilers in off gas grid areas.","false","Biography information for Roger Williams","Brecon and Radnorshire","Roger Williams","208043"
